'''TorrentFreak''' is a [[blog]] dedicated to reporting the latest news on the [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] protocol and [[file sharing]]. TorrentFreak was started in November 2005 by a [[Dutch people|Dutch]]man using the pseudonym "Ernesto Van Der Sar".<ref> {{cite web|url=http://uscpwned.blogspot.com/2007/05/final-project-interview-2-ernesto-of.html|title=Pwned: Final Project Interview #2: Ernesto of TorrentFreak.com|date=2007-05-14|last=Injijian|first=Allen|accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref><ref name=WSJ>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|last=Smith|first=Ethan|last2=McBride|first2=Sarah|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB121781125541508813.html|title=Web Piracy: The Enemy Within?|date=2008-08-04|accessdate=2010-06-14 }}</ref> He added "Smaran" to his staff in September 2006, as well as Andy "Enigmax" Maxwell in February 2007 and Ben Jones in May 2007.<ref name=WSJ/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/about/|title=About TorrentFreak|accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref>
According to Canadian law scholar [[Michael Geist]], TorrentFreak "is widely used as a source of original reporting on digital issues".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michaelgeist.ca/content/view/4971/125/ |title=The 2009 Copyright Consultation: Setting the Record Straight |date=2010-04-20 |accessdate=2010-06-14 |first=Michael |last=Geist}}</ref> Examples are [[The New York Times]]<ref>{{cite news |title='U.S. Shuts Down Web Sites in Piracy Crackdown |first=Ben |last=Sisaro |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/27/technology/27torrent.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-11-26 }}</ref> [[The Guardian]],<ref>{{cite news |title='BitTorrent: Copyright lawyers' favourite target reaches 200,000 lawsuits |first=Jemima |last=Kiss |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/pda/2011/aug/09/bittorrent-piracy |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2011-08-09 }}</ref> [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news |title='50,000 BitTorrent users sued for alleged illegal downloads |first=Julianne |last=Pepitone |url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/06/10/technology/bittorrent_lawsuits/index.htm |newspaper=[[CNN]] |date=2011-06-10 }}</ref> [[The Wall Street Journal]]<ref>{{cite news |title='Web Piracy: The Enemy Within? |first=Sarah |last=McBride |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB121781125541508813.html |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=2008-08-04 }}</ref> and [[De Standaard]].<ref>, {{cite journal |last=Van Cayseele |first=Patrick J. G. |last2=Vanormelingen |first2=Stijn |date=2009-02-26 |title=Prices and Network Effects in Two-Sided Markets: The Belgian Newspaper Industry |ssrn=1404392}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Lost' en het mysterie van de illegale downloads |first=Kristof |last=Hoefkens |url=http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=0H2QP9IS |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |date=2010-05-28 |page=36 |language=Dutch |trans_title='Lost' and the mystery of illegal downloads}}</ref><ref> {{cite news |title=Prince versus het internet |first=Kristof |last=Hoefkens |url=http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=NH2SJP84 |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |date=2010-07-08 |page=34 |language=Dutch |trans_title=Prince versus the internet}}</ref>
TorrentFreak's contents are [[free content]] under a [[Creative Commons]] [http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/ Attribution] license.
== Comcast BitTorrent throttling == {{see also|Comcast#Network neutrality}}
On August 17, 2007 TorrentFreak reported that [[Comcast]] had begun [[Bandwidth throttling|throttling]] its upload bandwidth, specifically against BitTorrent users. This made [[Seed (BitTorrent)|seeding]], which is an essential part of the BitTorrent protocol, effectively impossible.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lightreading.com/document.asp?doc_id=132115 |title=Comcast Takes on TorrentFreak |first=Ryan |last=Lawler |date=2007-08-21 |accessdate=2010-06-14 |publisher=Light Reading}}</ref> It was later determined that Comcast was using [[Sandvine]] products which implement network traffic shaping and policing, and include support for both blocking new and forcefully terminating established network connections. [[Comcast]] has denied these claims whenever they have been asked to comment. A guide, for customer service representatives when asked about Comcast's BitTorrent throttling, was leaked to [[The Consumerist]] on October 26, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://consumerist.com/consumer/leaks/comcasts-we-dont-throttle-bittorrent-internal-talking-points-memo-315791.php |title=Comcast's "We Don't Throttle BitTorrent" Internal Talking Points Memo |publisher=[[The Consumerist]] |date=2007-10-26 |accessdate=2010-06-14}}</ref>
